INTRODUCTION

In this homework, we are given a data which consists of different variables, these variables are given below. Main aim of this homework is to forecast the sales of the UGS for every quarter of the 2007 with time series regression. UGS can be defined as Unleaded gasoline sale in a given quarter. To be able to forecast these values, we first need to build a model. Since this is the time series, we are required to add trend and seasonality. At the following steps, we have done some variable addition with the help of lag values, their effect on the model is analyzed.

Followings are the variables that can be used while building the model.

UGS: Unleaded gasoline sale in a given quarter, RNUV: An index indicating the rate of new unleaded gasoline using vehicles being added to the traffic in a quarter, PU: Average price (adjusted with an index) of a liter of unleaded gasoline in a quarter, PG: Average price (adjusted with an index) of a liter of diesel gasoline in a quarter, NUGV: Number of unleaded gasoline using vehicles in the traffic, NDGV: Number of diesel gasoline using vehicles in the traffic (per 1000 people), GNPA: Agriculture component of Gross National Product (adjusted with an index), GNPC: Commerce component of Gross National Product (adjusted with an index), GNP: Grand total for GNP (agriculture, commerce and other components total).

As we can see from the plot, we have decreasing trend and the seasonality. By means of stationary, we can say that because of the decreasing trend in the data, we do not have the stationary mean however variance is stationary.

Auto correlation is drawn

AutoCorrelation <- acf(hw2_data_ts[,c("Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS.")],lag.max=28, plot = FALSE)
plot(AutoCorrelation, xlab = "Year",ylab= "Unleaded Gasoline Sale (UGS)",main = "Autocorrelation functions of the time series UGS")

The plot above represents the autocorrelation of the UGS values. Dashed lines shows the critical values and as can be seen from the data, lag1 and lag4 are above the critical values. This implies that while building the model, lag1 and lag4 values should be considered.

REGRESSION

Trend and seasonality are defined and added to the data. Besides, lag1 and lag4 values are found and seasonality is defined as factor while trend is numeric.

trend=c(1:32)
hw2_data$trend=trend
quartes_info=rep(1:4,8)
hw2_data$quartes_info=quartes_info

hw2_data$lagged_values_lag1= NA

for(i in 1:28){
  hw2_data$lagged_values_lag1[i+1] = hw2_data$"Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS."[i]
}

#hw2_data$lagged_values_lag1

hw2_data$lagged_values_lag4= NA

for(i in 1:28){
  hw2_data$lagged_values_lag4[i+4] = hw2_data$"Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS."[i]
}

#hw2_data$lagged_values_lag4

#summary(hw2_data)

hw2_data$quartes_info=as.factor(hw2_data$quartes_info)
hw2_data$trend=as.numeric(hw2_data$trend)

Model 1 Comments

It is important to note, Quarter should not be added to model, so first think to do is subtracting it from the data. Since we are doing backward selection, all other variables are used. While making addition or subtraction, we will focus on the variables significance,adjusted R^2 and Residual Standart Error values. At the beginning one of variables which have high Pr(>|t|) values will be eliminated.

Final Model Evaluation

With the variables we are given, the trend and seasonality factors, the above model is the best we have found. The one we have found is not guaranteed to be the best model that could be created. While building this method, we took some incentives thanks to the definitions of the variables. Besides, significance of the variables at the built model is also highly important factor to be considered. Adjusted R^2 and residual standard error are used for the comparison of the models. Finally, the best model has Adjusted R^2 value of 0.9679 and Residual Standard Error of 27090. In this final model, all of the variable that used in the model are significant, therefore we can conclude that our model is good enoguh to use at prediction.

Validity of our analysis

  1. Residual Analysis: By looking at the checkresiduals functions results, we can say that our assumptions for residuals are not satisfied in general. To have better understanding about this analysis, we have plotted the Q-Q plot. Autocorrelation of the residuals also seems to be problematic at some degree. It is good to remember that we added lag4 to our model but it did not improved the model, therefore it kept outside of the model.
  2. Significance of Coefficients: While building the model, significance of Coefficients are used. Addition and subtraction decision are based on the Significance of Coefficients, and at the final model all of the variables used are significant.

PREDICTION

pred_hw2_data=NA

hw2_data_test=hw2_data


for (i in 1:4){
  
  pred_hw2_data[i]=predict(final_model12,newdata=hw2_data_test[i+28,])
  if(i < 4){
     hw2_data$lagged_values_lag1[i+29] = pred_hw2_data[i]
  
  }
}

for (i in 1:4){
  print(paste("Prediction for", hw2_data$Quarter[i+28],"is",pred_hw2_data[i]))
 }

CONCLUSION

In this homework, our main aim was to predict the UGS sales of the quarters of the 2007. To be able to achieve that, first we tried to build the best model we can reach. Before building the model, trend seasonality, lag1 and lag4 values are added the data. The best model is produced by looking at the significance levels of the variables and checking the models residuals. We chose the backward selection method, this means that at the beginning we added all of the variables to the model. With the help of criteria I mentioned above, some of the variables are removed, however at some point we are also required to use forward selection. At some step, we tried to add lag values of the input variables however, they did not improved the model. Therefore, they are not in the final model. At the end, we reached the final model with all significant variables.
